## 4. Driver App / Dashboard

### Access

Driver logs in via shared page using Driver Name + Driver ID.
Role `driver` → redirects to Driver Dashboard.

### Global Driver Layout

The entire Driver App — every page — is wrapped in a single **Global DriverLayout** component that is **never unmounted** as the driver navigates between screens.

**This layout is responsible for:**
1. **Persistent socket connection** — connects to `driver_room_{driverId}` once on login and keeps the connection alive across all page navigation (Home, Profile, History, Active Trip). The socket does NOT disconnect or re-initialize when the driver changes screens.
2. **Global `new_booking` listener** — the `new_booking` event listener lives in the layout, not in any individual page. This means the incoming request overlay fires **regardless of which screen the driver is currently on**:
   - Driver is on the **Home screen** → overlay appears ✅
   - Driver is on the **Profile screen** → overlay appears ✅
   - Driver is on the **Trip History screen** → overlay appears ✅
   - Driver is on the **Active Trip screen** → overlay appears ✅ (stacked on top; driver must handle current trip first or deny the new one)
3. **Global `booking_status_update` / `booking_cancelled` listener** — handles client cancellations and status changes at the layout level so the driver is notified regardless of which screen they are on.
4. **Re-join on reconnect** — on every socket reconnect, the layout automatically re-joins `driver_room_{driverId}` and calls `GET /bookings/active?driverId=` to reconcile whether there is still an active trip to display.

**Implementation note:** The incoming request overlay must be rendered as a **portal or top-level component inside the layout**, rendered above all page content with a high z-index. It must not be placed inside any individual page component, otherwise it will only work on that page.

```
<DriverLayout>          ← socket lives here, global listeners live here
  <IncomingRequestOverlay />   ← rendered here, always on top, shows/hides via layout state
  <Routes>
    <Route path="/home"    element={<DriverHome />} />
    <Route path="/trip"    element={<ActiveTrip />} />
    <Route path="/history" element={<TripHistory />} />
    <Route path="/profile" element={<DriverProfile />} />
  </Routes>
</DriverLayout>
```

